The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, March 13, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, March 12: The government may mop up over Rs 10,400 crore from ONGC public offering, with disinvestment minister Arun Shourie not ruling out a selling price of Rs 750 per share at which the public offer has been oversubscribed more than three times, a day before the issue closes. Asked if the government could announce the selling price at Rs 750, going by the oversubscription of three times, Shourie said, Why not...We will try to take care of the interests of everyone, including the retail investors. 																								 Mumbai, March 12: The Securities and Exchange Board of India has barred the promoters of Aftek Infosys Ltd, including Ranjit Dhuru and Nitin Shukla, from buying, selling or dealing in securities for one year for indulging in fraudulent and unfair trade practices in the securities market.																								 Mumbai, March 12: ICICI Bank shareholders today approved the proposed public issue of a maximum of 15.5 crore shares to raise up to Rs 3,500 crore to strengthen the banks capital base and tap business opportunities.																								 New Delhi, March 12: The Centre today revised the norms for encashment of income tax refunds as part of its efforts to prevent frauds.																								 Basel, March 12: Novartis said it is considering combining with Frances Aventis, which is trying to fend off a 46.5 billion euros hostile takeover bid from Sanofi-Synthelabo SA.
